<br>
I've been studying the history of the Eucharist for a few weeks now, and finding history is largely against my Baptist view that the Lord's Supper is only symbolic.<br>
<br>
Respected early church fathers like Irenaeus, Ignatius, Justin Martyr, Tertullian and others spoke strongly on bread and wine being the literal body and blood of Christ, and spoke against them only being symbols.<br>
<br>
In the history of the church, there was really no other view (other than the bread and wine being literally Christ's flesh and blood) until the Reformation. And even here, I got a big surprise: even Luther held to the literal view, and argued intensely against other Protestants (like Zwingli) who can adopted the symbolic view.<br>
<br>
Even in scripture, I find my &quot;symbolic&quot; view falling away. In John 6, which I've read a hundred times before, I now see that Christ repeatedly affirms we are to eat his flesh and drink his blood. All the disciples have a hard time with this, and for obvious reasons. Many disciples even leave Christ over this, and when they leave, Christ *doesn't* say &quot;I'm just being symbolic, come back guys!&quot; - instead, he *repeats* his words, and then asks the apostles if they are going to leave to. This is difficult text from me to read and accept literally, but when I apply the &quot;grammatical, historical&quot; method of interpretation, I am left with little choice. John 6:55 especially - where Christ is making it the point that he's NOT being symbolic.<br>
<br>
Now I just have to figure out what to do about it. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Since my church does not believe in the literal body and blood in the Lord's Supper, and I'm starting to believe in the literal presence, should I refrain from partaking of our Baptist communion until I sort this out for myself? I don't want to partake in an &quot;unworthy manner&quot;.<br>
<br>
God bless,<br>
Brian <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=esdras>esdras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator<br>Sir Esdras, Brewmeister <br>of the Great White North</span><br>  Posts: 192<br> <font color=#B87333>(6/26/03 4:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www3.sympatico.ca/gsmorgan/images/ADPY005.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Eucharist</span><hr size=1> Obviously, I hold to the belief of transubstantiation (literally the body and blood of Christ) in the sacrament of the Eucharist.<br>
<br>
I rmember discussing this with those who take the symbolic view, and they point to the Gospels' account of the Last Supper where Jesus shares the bread and wine.  When you examine the original Greek, at this point Christ does, in fact, say something more along the lines of &quot;this is, as it were, my body&quot;... etc.  At the Last Supper, Jesus was actually speaking metaphorically, and this is the argument of many who see communion as symbolic.  However, when considered on a temporal basis, this makes sense.  Jesus had not yet been crucified, the sacrifice had not yet occured, so at that time the bread and wine was just that, bread and wine.  But when, as you rightly pointed out, John 6 is taken into account we see the whole picture.  It all must be combined.  Jesus tells us in John 6 that His body is true food and His blood is true drink.  Then we go to the last supper as see what we are to use for all time when we gather to remember His sacrifice.  After His sacrifice, the miracle will be that the bread and wine is the body and blood.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I kind of rambled there.  It is a hard thing to come to grips with, but as I have believed this since my first communion when I was 7, I just see it as what is. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
