<br>
I've been reading more on this, as I have never viewed communion as anything other than a service in  'remembrance' of Christ.  I enjoy studying from <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Matthew Henry's Commentaries</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and thought you might find his words interesting on this topic too: (he wrote several pages, but I'll shorten it here)<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What is meant by the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>flesh and the blood of Christ</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  It is called (John 6:53) <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the flesh of the Son of man, and his blood.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  It is said to be given for the life of the world, that is, First, Instead of the life of the world, which was forfeited by sin, Christ gives his own flesh as a ransom.  Secondly, In order to the life of the world,  to purchase a general offer of eternal life to all the world.  So that the flesh and blood of the Son of man denote Christ and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>him crucified,</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and the redemption wrought out by him.  The promises of the covenant, and eternal life;  these are called the flesh and the blood of Christ.<br>
<br>
1.  Because they are purchased by the breaking of his body, and the sheddidng of his blood.  2.  Because they are meat and drink to our souls.  He had before compared himself to bread, which is necessary food;  here to flesh, which is delicious.  It is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>meat indeed, and drink indeed;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  in opposition to the shows and shadows with which the world shams off those that feed upon it.<br>
<br>
What is meant by eating this flesh and drinking this blood.  It is certain that it means neither more nor less than believing in Christ.  Believing in Christ includes these four things, which eating and drinking do:  First, it implies an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>appetite</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to Christ.  This spiritual eating and drinking begins with hungering and thirsting (Matt. v.6)  &quot;Give me Christ or else I die&quot;.  Secondly, An <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>application</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of Christ to ourselves.  Meat looked upon will not nourish us, but meat fed upon.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>We must so accept of Christ as to appropriate him to ourselves.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Thirdly,  A delight in Christ and his salvation.  The doctrine of Christ crucified must be meat and drink to us, most pleasant and delightful.  Fourthly, A <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>derivation of nourishment</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> from him and a dependence upon him for the support and comfort of our spiritual life, and the strength, growth, and vigour of the new man.<br>
<br>
When afterwards he would institute some outward sensible signs, by which to represent our communicating of the benefits of his death, he chose those of eating and drinking, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>and made them sacramental actions. </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I've been aware of the two views for a while, and honestly, it isn't such a leap for me to believe that Christ is 'within' the bread and wine.  Here's why...<br>
<br>
we are talking about a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>sacrament</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, a way in which we receive God's grace towards Christian growth/sanctification (for lack of a better more thought-out definition)...and in this view, I have always considered that I am 'communing' with Jesus Christ when I partake of the Lord's Supper.  Even in my view of this service as a 'remembering' our Lord's sacrifice, I still yet believe in a living God that continually fills us with his spirit.<br>
<br>
A study on the fullness on the Holy Spirit led me to certainty that being 'filled' with the Holy Spirit as a believer is NOT a one time occurance, it is an on-going process....which has led me to a better understanding of what a 'sacrament' is.<br>
<br>
